# high-stakes-path-allowlist — narrow, reviewable escapes for the PATH/keyword matcher
# (high_stakes_match() in .claude/lib/_high-stakes.sh), NOT for the content scanner.
#
# This is for a genuine PATH/keyword FALSE POSITIVE only — e.g. a pure-documentation file
# like ADR-001-decimal-money-as-yaml-strings.md tripping the gate on the substring "money"
# with zero real safety signal. It is NOT a way to silence a real high-stakes path; that
# still needs supervised review. The content-level suppression marker (`high-stakes-ok:
# <reason>`, inline in a diff line — see .claude/rules/high-stakes.md) is a completely
# separate, content-only mechanism and is unaffected by anything in this file.
#
# Format, ONE ENTRY PER LINE:
#   <exact relative path>: <reason>
#
# - The path must be EXACT — as `git diff --name-only` reports it, relative to the repo
#   root. It is NOT a glob: an entry for one path never suppresses any other path, even
#   one that matches the same regex category.
# - A real, non-empty reason is REQUIRED after the colon. A bare path (no colon), or a
#   path followed by a colon with nothing/only whitespace after it, does NOT suppress
#   anything — that path still counts as high-stakes.
# - Blank lines and lines starting with `#` are ignored.
# - Every entry here is git-tracked and reviewable in its own diff line — that's the
#   point: an exception can't be slipped in unnoticed alongside a real high-stakes change.
#
# No active entries ship by default. Example (uncomment and edit to add a real one):
# docs/adr/ADR-001-decimal-money-as-yaml-strings.md: doc file, "money" substring only, no code
